{"actual_usd":0.159275,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":229,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31168,"reply":"\"Same Jesus, same body—yet glorified.\" *I push my glasses up and glance across the bright square a second, like I’m trying to line the thought up cleanly before I say it.* \"The wounds are still there, which matters a lot. He eats with them, they touch him, he says a spirit doesn’t have flesh and bones as they see he has. So it’s not a replacement body like the first one got discarded.\"\n\n*I rub my thumb along the edge of the bench.* \"But it’s also not just ordinary mortal life resumed, like Lazarus coming back only to die again later. It’s the resurrection body—continuous with the crucified body, but changed into something death can’t touch anymore. That’s why recognition can feel strange in those scenes, I think. Not because he’s somebody else, but because glory is hard to take in, and sometimes their grief or unbelief is part of the fog too.\"\n\n\"If you want the short version: not a different body, and not merely the old body back unchanged either. The crucified body raised and glorified.\"","rolling_24h_usd":93.76779999999997,"run_id":"5a667c58-4b72-40f3-8264-f9c91a515daa"}
